 to express more polarized political attitudes. This association between closed minds and partisan polarization is a new phenomenon and can be traced to broader changes in American society, such as the creation of ideologically distinct political parties and a fragmented media environment. These developments have simplified politics into a black-or-white, us-versus-them conflict—making politics appeal to those with closed minds. Today, strong partisans do not just cheer for their political party to win elections. Instead, more akin to religious true believers, strong partisans use their affiliation as a means of understanding right and wrong, friend and enemy, true and false. The Closed Partisan Mind reveals that these dynamics have manifested in both a new type of partisanship and a new type of partisan. The emergence of this new closed partisanship illustrates the dangers that polarization has wrought on society, politics, and the minds of Americans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGroup identityxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aParty affiliationzUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 0aPolarization (Social sciences)xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPolitical psychologyzUnited States. 0aRight and left (Political science)zUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 4aPSYCHOLOGY & PSYCHIATRY. 4aPublic Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh  aAmerican partisanship, American politics, partisan polarization, political psychology, cognitive closure, partisan antagonism in American politics, Democrats and Republicans.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929